pan><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">current efforts of the Malawi Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(with support from NAD, CBM and SADPD) to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> promote</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inclusion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the public sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NAD has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">outlined key</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> practical</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> steps </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">towards </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mainstreaming disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">development programs and services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> NAD also recommends that DFID support the development, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">implement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and documentation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Community Based Rehabilitation (CBR) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">initiatives as a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">human </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rights-based, multi sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disability inclusion development approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> implement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the UN</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (UN</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CRPD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  NAD offers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the effectiveness of CBR to facilitate disability inclusion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in development </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">four </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">brief case stories. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">The Norwegian Association of Disabled (NAD)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Norwegian Association of Disabled (NAD) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is an independent disabled pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rsons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ organization (DPO) that supports the promotion of equal rights, social participatio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n and inclusion of disabled persons in Norway and abroad, the latter through international development cooperation partnerships in Africa and Palestine.  For more than 30 years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NAD has used a twin track approach in its international work, which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">includes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support to DPOs and their umbrella organizations to facilitate and build capacity in effective advocacy and lobbying for the rights of disabled persons and support to Community Based Rehabilitation (CBR) programs implemented by local partners (mainly gover</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nment ministries).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Justification for disability inclusion in development work </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Links between disability, poverty, marginalization and exclusion are well established. The 2011 WHO/World Bank </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">World Report on Disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> estimates that nearly 200 million pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ople with disabilities experience considerable difficulties in functioning. The majority of disabled persons live in developing countries under poverty conditions. They are among the world’s most vulnerable and least empowered groups, experiencing stigma a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd discrimination with limited access to health care, education and livelihood opportunities. Disability issues are being increasingly recognized in the international development debate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rom both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> individual</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and global perspective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, development interven</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tions will fail unless disability issues and disabled persons are included.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID, which has played a key role in getting disability on the agenda, now has the potential to consolidate and build on this progress and to lead the way in securing the polici</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es, systems </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and approaches that will ensure that disability issues and disabled people are included at all levels. DFID should be ambitious but realistic by adopting a phased, strategic approach to including disability/disabled persons at all levels and ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">anging attitudes about disability at all levels.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Recommendations for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">action: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">concrete ways to include </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">disability in DFID’s development work</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Based on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">extensive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, NAD would like to contribute the following concrete </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for ways in which DFID can promote disability inclusion in its development work through a two-pronged approach as follows: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Provide short to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">medium-term </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technical and financial support for promoting disability inclusion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the public sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through support of a national mainstreaming strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Provi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">long</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-term </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technical and financial support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> implementation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and documentation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CBR programs, in particular CBR programs anchored in and supported by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID’s country partner </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government at all levels, with the long-term goal and a clear plan for the government to eventually assume full responsibility for CBR in the country.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Provision of technical support to the national partner may be outsourced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to a N</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(s) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with disability/CBR expertise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Support of disability inclusion (‘mainstreaming’) at national government level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The following suggestions offer key steps towards </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mainstreaming disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">development programs and services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  They are drawn from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">current efforts of the Malawi Government to mainstream disability in the public sector with technical and financial support from NAD, CBM, and the Secretariat of the African Decade of Persons with Disabilities (SADPD) in collaboration with the Federation o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f Disability Organizations in Malawi (FEDOMA).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sensitize DFID program staff so that they </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">knowledge and understanding of key international instruments</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on disability rights and inclusive development, as well as local legal and policy frameworks that c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ould support mainstreaming efforts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and existing programs and services that target disability issues. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is essential that DFID staff understand the following terms/concepts: inclusive development, disability as a rights and development issue, effective l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">obbying and advocacy, and disability mainstreaming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(to include strategies for mainstreaming disability, development of output/outcome indicators and monitoring/evaluation tools).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sign a memorandum of understanding with DFID local partners, government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ministries and or departments to prioritize mainstreaming of disability issues as one of the pre-conditions for accessing financial and technical support from DFID.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Identify/appoint disability focal points in DFID local partners in each of the countries t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hat benefit from DFID support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Build capacity of focal points in DFID local partners in terms/concepts outlined in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.1 above</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and in concrete strategies that DFID partners could use to meaningfully mainstream and monitor program outputs and outcomes. It wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uld help for DFID to partner with existing local expertise during development and execution of the training program. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Establish a task force on disability mainstreaming for on-going mentoring of the partner organization/ministry to include local expertise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> drawn from the line ministry for disability, DPOs and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disability mainstreaming focal point in DFID country offices.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In partnership with local line ministries for disability and local federations of disabled persons and other international development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> partners that champion disability issues, develop disability awareness material and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dissemination strategy.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Maintain a strategic focus on implementation of the UNCRPD through support to DPOs, NGOs, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government structures/duty bearers, rather than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">creating parallel structures through service delivery.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Require and support monitoring, documentation and research to identify and document results for disabled persons as a result of disability mainstreaming initiatives at all levels. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Support of CBR pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">grams</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  It is suggested that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID provide financial and technical support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for the development and implementation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of CBR programs through arrangements made with national ministries in its development cooperation countries.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disability needs to be understood</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> primarily as a social and human rights issue. CBR is a human rights-based, multi sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disability inclusion development approach which addresses the needs and inclusion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">--</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and participation by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-- </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled children, youth and adults in a family and co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mmunity context.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CBR’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scope includes promotion of disability inclusion in – and linking disabled persons </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and their families </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with -- initiatives </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the areas of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">health, education, social inclusion, livelihood and empowerment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  CBR offers a flexible approa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ch that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adapted to each country’s context and the local community’s needs.  CBR is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">viewed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by WHO as the most important tool for implementation of the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (UNCRPD).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The following brief case stories from CBR programs supported by NAD are among many such CBR stories that illustrate results of disability inclusion in development </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">initiatives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">FEDOMA’s long</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> standing efforts to engage the media to raise the issue of rights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of disabled persons bore fruit when journalists in a national newspaper independently uncovered that disabled children were taught in rooms previously used as toilets in a school in Blantyre, Malawi. The media outlet gave the story a lot of coverage and t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he reaction was immediate. The local member of Parliament got engaged and even the mobile provider Zain initiated a text message campaign to its customers which spread the story nationwide. After initial reluctance on the part of the local authorities and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">headmaster of the school, the children were moved to a new and bigger classroom on the same premises. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The partners in this project are FEDOMA and NAD.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Microfinance and Disability Project in Uganda aims for disabled persons to enjoy equal and fair acce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ss to quality financial products and services. The project is doing targeted lobby and advocacy activities towards a selected segment of microfinance institutions in Uganda and also training of economically active men and women with disabilities. This has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resulted in close collaboration with the Center  for Financial Inclusion at ACCION where ‘disability’ has become a new dimension in financial inclusion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> increasingly inclusive microfinance institutions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and disabled persons being awarded as outstanding entrepreneurs. On a personal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">level,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disabled persons are able to provide for themselves and their families, gaining independence and a sense of self-worth while at the same time contributing to the economy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The partners in this project are NUDIPU, AMFIU and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NAD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBR program implemented by MACOHA in Malawi is working to promote more inclusive practices in local communities to improve the access of disabled children and adults to their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rights, entitlements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and available services and to increase their participation in their communities.  CBR workers and District CBR Committees report that their efforts to raise the awareness of local magistrates and chiefs on the rights of disabled perso</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ns are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">achieving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">results.  After encouraging these local leaders to practice an inclusive justice system, an increasing number of disabled persons, many of whom are women, have reported violations of their rights.  Raising awareness about the right of disa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bled persons to earn a livelihood has resulted in local chiefs including disabled persons in all public works projects.  For example, in the Traditional Authority Somba in Blantyre district, after many years of exclusion, it is now a familiar sight to find</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disabled people among those clearing a road and receiving fertilizer or cash for their work.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The partners in this project are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MACOHA, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">para-statal organization in Malawi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">implements the CBR program</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and NAD.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he Rehabilitation Program in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Palestine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CBR </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cornerstone,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has recently implemented a 3-year project aimed at contributing to increased promotion and protection of the rights and entitlements of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children and adults from the Arab-Palestinian community in East Je</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rusalem.   As a result of action taken by lawyers acting within a legal framework to secure the rights of disabled persons in East Jerusalem, the Israeli Ministry of Transportation has committed to making the three central bus terminals in East Jerusalem a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ccessible by 2014 and has agreed to expand the number of bus lines that will ultimately be made accessible.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The partners in this project are Bizchut (an Israeli disability rights organization), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the EU, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Diakonia and NAD.</span></p><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">For example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">UNCRPD (2006), Convention on the Rights of the Child (1989), the Universal Declaration on Human Rights (1948) and the UN Standard Rules on Equalization of Opportunities for Persons with Disabilities (1983)</span></p></body></html>